[2] Spain (Anti-vaccine movement)
Date: Sat 13 Oct 2012 [in Spanish, trans. Mod.JT, edited]
Source: Fuente: La Verdad, Espana
http://www.laverdad.es/murcia/v/20121013/cultura/nueve-ninos-muertos-sarampion-20121013.html


Anti-vaccination movements, with arguments not sustained by the evidence, produce serious harm to society. Often, they are responsible, in part, for the decline in vaccination rates that trigger outbreaks of easily preventable diseases.

In recent years, we are witnessing the resurgence of measles, accompanied by its complications, not only in Spain but in the surrounding countries. In 2011, there were more than 30 000 cases of measles in Europe, with 9 deaths in young children, which could have been avoided if the number of people vaccinated had not fallen.

Probably one of the reasons why these beliefs persist is the ignorance that exists in relation to the long process of development of vaccines, which sometimes take many years of development and safety testing before release for general administration, a process that requires greater stringency than in the case of most of the other drugs that many of us take on a regular basis.

--
