[4] China (Shaanxi)
Date 14 Oct 2012
Source: Xi'an Evening News [in Chinese, machine trans. edited]
http://healthmap.org/admin/disp.php?id=1341720


A Xi'an Evening News reporter learned from a sub-provincial city immunization planning meeting held recently in Xi'an that the measles epidemic for the year up to September 2012 fell to a record low. The monitoring data showed that the total incidence as of 1 Sep 2012 was down to single digits.

Measles is an acute respiratory infection caused by measles virus. After onset of fever, cough, runny nose, conjunctival hyperemia, and body rash, the disease is often complicated by pneumonia, and may endanger the lives of infants and young children. It is spread by respiratory droplets. In recent years, the incidence of measles in Xi'an reached a peak in spring and summer. More than 80 percent of the cases are observed in children up to 14 years of age.

CDC staff are asking parents to ensure that school-age children are fully immunized. The 1st inoculation should be at 2 months followed by a 2nd inoculation at 18-24 months.

At the same time, student dormitories and other public and communal living spaces should be regularly ventilated; clothing and bedding should be aired, and hand-washing and personal hygiene strictly observed.

The city has completed nearly 200 new vaccination clinics located in urban community health service centers and township hospitals capable of vaccinating 2000 to 4000 children, the aim being to achieve a vaccination rate of greater than 95 percent and complete eradication of the disease among the non-migrant population.

[Byline: Liang Fan]

--
